# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: en-50128-railway
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:en-50128-railway/cenelec] CENELEC is a non-profit organization under Belgian law, based in Brussels.
[src:en-50128-railway/cenelec] The members are the national electrotechnical standardization bodies of most European countries.
[src:en-50128-railway/cenelec] The standards are published in three official, authoritative language versions (in cooperation with CEN, unless something else is agreed): English, French and German.
[src:en-50128-railway/cenelec] Members that have another official language then make a national translation.
[src:en-50128-railway/cenelec] English versions are generally the primary references.
[src:en-50128-railway/cenelec] As of 2026, CENELEC has 34 full members, including all 27 EU members, 3 EFTA members, as well as North Macedonia, Serbia, Turkey, and the United Kingdom.
[src:en-50128-railway/cenelec] Before that two organizations were responsible for electrotechnical standardization: CENELCOM and CENEL.
[src:en-50128-railway/cenelec] After the Dresden Agreement (1996), CENELEC coordinates standard development activities with IEC.
[src:en-50128-railway/cenelec] Older IEC standards were converted in 1997 by adding 60000, for example IEC 27 became IEC 60027 and the same standards are also published in the EN 60000 series to indicate adoption by CENELEC as a European standard; for example IEC 60034 is also available as EN 60034.
[src:en-50128-railway/cenelec] Regional European standards issued by CENELEC, which are not adopted IEC standards, are numbered in the EN 50000 series.
[src:en-50128-railway/cenelec] As of 2017, more than 90% of the standards passed by CENELEC used the Dresden Agreement process.
[src:en-50128-railway/cenelec] The alternative process in which a member National Committee proposes a standard is called the Vilamoura process (or procedure).
[src:en-50128-railway/cenelec] The Dresden Agreement was updated with the Frankfurt Agreement in October 2016, and decisions are detailed in CENELEC Guide 13 (2016).
[src:en-50128-railway/cenelec] Following the publication of this guide, IEC standards adopted by CENELEC shall be referenced as "EN IEC 6xxxx".
[src:en-50128-railway/cenelec] For a proposal to pass, 71% of members need be in favor (according to weighted system above) or 71% of EEA members need be in favor, excluding Switzerland.
[src:en-50128-railway/cenelec] The weighted voting standard was maintained at 71%, meaning that if the 17 largest-weight countries vote for a standard it will pass this also means the top 50% by weight countries voting in favor.
[src:en-50128-railway/cenelec] If a proposal does not pass this way, a second vote taking into account only EU members is taken, with the threshold again being 71%.
[src:en-50128-railway/cenelec] However, unlike EU member states, non-EU CENELEC member countries are not required to transfer EN standards into national standards, although they usually do so.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] CBTC is a signalling standard defined by the IEEE 1474 standard.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] The original version was introduced in 1999 and updated in 2004.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] The aim was to create consistency and standardisation between digital railway signalling systems that allow for an increase in train capacity through what the standard defines as high-resolution train location determination.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] The standard therefore does not require the use of moving block railway signalling, but in practice this is the most common arrangement.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] Traditional signalling systems detect trains in discrete sections of the track called 'blocks', each protected by signals that prevent a train entering an occupied block.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] Since every block is a fixed section of track, these systems are referred to as fixed block systems.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] In a moving block CBTC system the protected section for each train is a "block" that moves with and trails behind it, and provides continuous communication of the train's exact position via radio, inductive loop, etc.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] As a result, Bombardier opened the world's first radio-based CBTC system at San Francisco airport's automated people mover (APM) in February 2003.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] A few months later, in June 2003, Alstom introduced the railway application of its radio technology on the Singapore North East Line.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] CBTC has its origins in the loop-based systems developed by Alcatel SEL (later Thales, now Hitachi Rail) for the Bombardier Automated Rapid Transit (ART) systems in Canada during the mid-1980s.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] These systems, which were also referred to as transmission-based train control (TBTC), made use of inductive loop transmission techniques for track to train communication, introducing an alternative to track circuit based communication.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] As with new application of any technology, some problems arose at the beginning, mainly due to compatibility and interoperability aspects.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] However, there have been relevant improvements since then, and currently the reliability of the radio-based communication systems has grown significantly.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] Moreover, it is important to highlight that not all the systems using radio communication technology are considered to be CBTC systems.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] CBTC systems are modern railway signaling systems that can mainly be used in urban railway lines (either light or heavy) and APMs, although it could also be deployed on commuter lines.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] For main lines, a similar system might be the European Railway Traffic Management System ERTMS Level 3 (not yet fully defined ).
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] In the modern CBTC systems the trains continuously calculate and communicate their status via radio to the wayside equipment distributed along the line.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] This status includes, among other parameters, the exact position, speed, travel direction and braking distance.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] This information allows calculation of the area potentially occupied by the train on the track.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] It also enables the wayside equipment to define the points on the line that must never be passed by the other trains on the same track.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] These points are communicated to make the trains automatically and continuously adjust their speed while maintaining the safety and comfort (jerk) requirements.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] So, the trains continuously receive information regarding the distance to the preceding train and are then able to adjust their safety distance accordingly.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] From the signalling system perspective, the first figure shows the total occupancy of the leading train by including the whole blocks which the train is located on.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] This is due to the fact that it is impossible for the system to know exactly where the train actually is within these blocks.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] Therefore, the fixed block system only allows the following train to move up to the last unoccupied block's border.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] In a moving block system as shown in the second figure, the train position and its braking curve is continuously calculated by the trains, and then communicated via radio to the wayside equipment.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] Thus, the wayside equipment is able to establish protected areas, each one called Limit of Movement Authority (LMA), up to the nearest obstacle (in the figure the tail of the train in front).
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] Movement Authority (MA) is the permission for a train to move to a specific location within the constraints of the infrastructure and with supervision of speed.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] End of Authority is the location to which the train is permitted to proceed and where target speed is equal to zero.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] End of Movement is the location to which the train is permitted to proceed according to an MA.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] When transmitting an MA, it is the end of the last section given in the MA.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] It is important to mention that the occupancy calculated in these systems must include a safety margin for location uncertainty (in yellow in the figure) added to the length of the train.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] Both of them form what is usually called 'Footprint'.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] This safety margin depends on the accuracy of the odometry system in the train.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] CBTC systems based on moving block allows the reduction of the safety distance between two consecutive trains.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] This distance is varying according to the continuous updates of the train location and speed, maintaining the safety requirements.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] This results in a reduced headway between consecutive trains and an increased transport capacity.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] Modern CBTC systems allow different levels of automation or grades of automation (GoA), as defined and classified in the IEC 62290–1.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] In fact, CBTC is not a synonym for "driverless" or "automated trains" although it is considered as a basic enabler technology for this purpose.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] CBTC systems allow optimal use of the railway infrastructure as well as achieving maximum capacity and minimum headway between operating trains, while maintaining the safety requirements.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] These systems are suitable for the new highly demanding urban lines, but also to be overlaid on existing lines in order to improve their performance.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] Of course, in the case of upgrading existing lines the design, installation, test and commissioning stages are much more critical.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] This is mainly due to the challenge of deploying the overlying system without disrupting the revenue service.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] The evolution of the technology and the experience gained in operation over the last 30 years means that modern CBTC systems are more reliable and less prone to failure than older train control systems.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] CBTC systems normally have less wayside equipment and their diagnostic and monitoring tools have been improved, which makes them easier to implement and, more importantly, easier to maintain.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] CBTC technology is evolving, making use of the latest techniques and components to offer more compact systems and simpler architectures.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] For instance, with the advent of modern electronics it has been possible to build in redundancy so that single failures do not adversely impact operational availability.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] Moreover, these systems offer complete flexibility in terms of operational schedules or timetables, enabling urban rail operators to respond to the specific traffic demand more swiftly and efficiently and to solve traffic congestion problems.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] In fact, automatic operation systems have the potential to significantly reduce the headway and improve the traffic capacity compared to manual driving systems.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] Finally, it is important to mention that the CBTC systems have proven to be more energy efficient than traditional manually driven systems.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] The use of new functionalities, such as automatic driving strategies or a better adaptation of the transport offer to the actual demand, allows significant energy savings reducing the power consumption.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] The primary risk of an electronic train control system is that if the communications link between any of the trains is disrupted, all or part of the system might have to enter a failsafe state until the problem is remedied.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] Depending on the severity of the communication loss, this state can range from vehicles temporarily reducing speed, coming to a halt or operating in a degraded mode until communications are re-established.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] If communication outage is permanent, some sort of contingency operation must be implemented which may consist of manual operation using absolute block or, in the worst case, the substitution of an alternative form of transportation.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] As a result, high availability of CBTC systems is crucial for proper operation, especially if such systems are used to increase transport capacity and reduce headway.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] System redundancy and recovery mechanisms must then be thoroughly checked to achieve a high robustness in operation.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] With the increased availability of the CBTC system, there is also a need for extensive training and periodical refresh of system operators on the recovery procedures.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] In fact, one of the major system hazards in CBTC systems is the probability of human error and improper application of recovery procedures if the system becomes unavailable.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] Communications failures can result from equipment malfunction, electromagnetic interference, weak signal strength or saturation of the communications medium.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] In this case, an interruption can result in a service brake or emergency brake application as real time situational awareness is a critical safety requirement for CBTC and if these interruptions are frequent enough it could seriously impact service.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] This is the reason why, historically, CBTC systems first implemented radio communication systems in 2003, when the required technology was mature enough for critical applications.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] In systems with poor line of sight or spectrum/bandwidth limitations a larger than anticipated number of transponders may be required to enhance the service.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] This is usually more of an issue with applying CBTC to existing transit systems in tunnels that were not designed from the outset to support it.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] An alternate method to improve system availability in tunnels is the use of leaky feeder cable that, while having higher initial costs (material + installation) achieves a more reliable radio link.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] With the emerging services over open ISM radio bands (i.e.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] Such decision would help standardize CBTC systems across the market (a growing demand from most operators) and ensure availability for those critical systems.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] As a CBTC system is required to have high availability and particularly, allow for a graceful degradation, a secondary method of signaling might be provided to ensure some level of non-degraded service upon partial or complete CBTC unavailability.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] This is particularly relevant for brownfield implementations (lines with an already existing signalling system) where the infrastructure design cannot be controlled and coexistence with legacy systems is required, at least, temporarily.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] For example, the BMT Canarsie Line in New York City was outfitted with a backup automatic block signaling system capable of supporting 12 trains per hour (tph), compared with the 26 tph of the CBTC system.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] Although this is a rather common architecture for resignalling projects, it can negate some of the cost savings of CBTC if applied to new lines.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] This is still a key point in the CBTC development (and is still being discussed), since some providers and operators argue that a fully redundant architecture of the CBTC system may however achieve high availability values by itself.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] In principle, CBTC systems may be designed with centralized supervision systems in order to improve maintainability and reduce installation costs.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] If so, there is an increased risk of a single point of failure that could disrupt service over an entire system or line.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] Fixed block systems usually work with distributed logic that are normally more resistant to such outages.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] Therefore, a careful analysis of the benefits and risks of a given CBTC architecture (centralized vs. distributed) must be done during system design.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] When CBTC is applied to systems that previously ran under complete human control with operators working on sight it may actually result in a reduction in capacity (albeit with an increase in safety).
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] This is because CBTC operates with less positional certainty than human sight and also with greater margins for error as worst-case train parameters are applied for the design (e.g. guaranteed emergency brake rate vs. nominal brake rate).
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] For instance, CBTC introduction in Philly's Center City trolley tunnel resulted initially in a marked increase in travel time and corresponding decrease in capacity when compared with the unprotected manual driving.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] This was the offset to finally eradicate vehicle collisions which on-sight driving cannot avoid and showcases the usual conflicts between operation and safety.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] **CBTC onboard equipment**, including ATP and ATO subsystems in the vehicles.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] **Train to wayside communication subsystem**, currently based on radio links.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] CBTC technology has been (and is being) successfully implemented for a variety of applications as shown in the figure below (mid 2011).
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] Despite the difficulty, the table below tries to summarize and reference the main radio-based CBTC systems deployed around the world as well as those ongoing projects being developed.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] Besides, the table distinguishes between the implementations performed over existing and operative systems (brownfield) and those undertaken on completely new lines (greenfield).
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] With train attendants who monitor door status, and drive trains in the event of a disruption.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] With train attendants (T\train captains) who drive trains in the event of a disruption.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] With train attendants (train captains) who drive trains in the event of a disruption.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] Upgraded from Siemens Trainguard LZB700M CTC in 2009.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] With train attendants who drive trains in the event of a disruption.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] These train attendants are on standby in the train.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] With train attendants (Rovers) who drive trains in the event of a disruption.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] A test track was retrofitted in 2012; the line's other tracks will be retrofitted by the early 2020s.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] The entire line is scheduled to be fully upgraded by 2022.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] Train conductors will be located aboard the train because other parts of the routes using the Queens Boulevard Line will not be equipped with CBTC.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] Train conductors will be located aboard the train because other parts of the routes using the Eighth Avenue Line will not be equipped with CBTC.
[src:en-50128-railway/communications-based-train-control] To be fully operational after the delivery of the 13 Alstom Metropolis BM4 trains.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Most forms of train control involve movement authority being passed from those responsible for each section of a rail network (e.g. a signalman or stationmaster) to the train crew.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The set of rules and the physical equipment used to accomplish this determine what is known as the *method of working* (UK), *method of operation* (US) or *safe-working* (Aus.).
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Not all these methods require the use of physical signals, and some systems are specific to single-track railways.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The earliest rail cars were hauled by horses or mules.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] A mounted flagman on a horse preceded some early trains.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Hand and arm signals were used to direct the "train drivers".
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Foggy and poor-visibility conditions later gave rise to flags and lanterns.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Wayside signalling dates back as far as 1832, and used elevated flags or balls that could be seen from afar.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The simplest form of operation, at least in terms of equipment, is to run the system according to a timetable.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Every train crew understands and adheres to a fixed schedule.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Trains may only run on each track section at a scheduled time, during which they have 'possession' and no other train may use the same section.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] When trains run in opposite directions on a single-track railway, meeting points ("meets") are scheduled, at which each train must wait for the other at a passing place.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Neither train is permitted to move before the other has arrived.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] In the US, the display of two green flags (green lights at night) is an indication that another train is following the first and the waiting train must wait for the next train to pass.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] In addition, the train carrying the flags gives eight blasts on the whistle as it approaches.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The waiting train must return eight blasts before the flag carrying train may proceed.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The timetable system has several disadvantages.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] First, there is no positive confirmation that the track ahead is clear, only that it is scheduled to be clear.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] A second problem is the system's inflexibility.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Trains cannot be added, delayed, or rescheduled without advance notice.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] A third problem is a corollary of the second: the system is inefficient.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] To provide flexibility, the timetable must give trains a broad allocation of time to allow for delays, so the line is not in the possession of each train for longer than is otherwise necessary.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Nonetheless, this system permits operation on a vast scale, with no requirements for any kind of communication that travels faster than a train.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Timetable operation was the normal mode of operation in North America in the early days of the railroad.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] With the advent of the telegraph in 1841, a more sophisticated system became possible because this provided a means whereby messages could be transmitted ahead of the trains.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The telegraph allows the dissemination of any timetable changes, known as *train orders*.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] These allow the cancellation, rescheduling and addition of train services.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] North American practice meant that train crews generally received their orders at the next station at which they stopped, or were sometimes handed up to a locomotive 'on the run' via a long staff.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Train orders allowed dispatchers to set up meets at sidings, force a train to wait in a siding for a priority train to pass, and to maintain at least one block spacing between trains going the same direction.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Timetable and train order operation was commonly used on American railroads until the 1960s, including some quite large operations such as the Wabash Railroad and the Nickel Plate Road.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Train order traffic control was used in Canada until the late 1980s on the Algoma Central Railway and some spurs of the Canadian Pacific Railway.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Timetable and train order was not used widely outside North America, and has been phased out in favour of radio dispatch on many light-traffic lines and electronic signals on high-traffic lines.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] More details of North American operating methods is given below.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] A similar method, known as 'Telegraph and Crossing Order' was used on some busy single lines in the UK during the 19th century.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] However, a series of head-on collisions resulted from authority to proceed being wrongly given or misunderstood by the train crew - the worst of which was the collision between Norwich and Brundall, Norfolk, in 1874.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] As a result, the system was phased out in favour of token systems.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Trains cannot collide with each other if they are not permitted to occupy the same section of track at the same time, so railway lines are divided into sections known as *blocks*.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] In normal circumstances, only one train is permitted in each block at a time.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This principle forms the basis of most railway safety systems.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Blocks can either be fixed (block limits are fixed along the line) or moving blocks (ends of blocks defined relative to moving trains).
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] On double tracked railway lines, which enabled trains to travel in one direction on each track, it was necessary to space trains far enough apart to ensure that they could not collide.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This was called "time interval working".
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] If a train had passed very recently, the following train was expected to slow down to allow more space to develop.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The watchmen had no way of knowing whether a train had cleared the line ahead, so if a preceding train stopped for any reason, the crew of a following train would have no way of knowing unless it was clearly visible.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] As a result, accidents were common in the early days of railways.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] With the invention of the electrical telegraph, it became possible for staff at a station or signal box to send a message (usually a specific number of rings on a bell) to confirm that a train had passed and that a specific block was clear.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This was called the "absolute block system".
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Fixed mechanical signals began to replace hand signals from the 1830s.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] These were originally worked locally, but it later became normal practice to operate all the signals on a particular block with levers grouped together in a signal box.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] When a train passed into a block, a signalman would protect that block by setting its signal to 'danger'.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] When an 'all clear' message was received, the signalman would move the signal into the 'clear' position.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The absolute block system came into use gradually during the 1850s and 1860s and became mandatory in the United Kingdom after Parliament passed legislation in 1889 following a number of accidents, most notably the Armagh rail disaster.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This required block signalling for all passenger railways, together with interlocking, both of which form the basis of modern signalling practice today.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Similar legislation was passed by the United States around the same time.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Not all blocks are controlled using fixed signals.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] On some single track railways in the UK, particularly those with low usage, it is common to use token systems that rely on the train driver's physical possession of a unique token as authority to occupy the line, normally in addition to fixed signals.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Before allowing a train to enter a block, a signalman must be certain that it is not already occupied.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] When a train leaves a block, they must inform the signalman controlling entry to the block.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Even if the signalman receives advice that the previous train has left a block, they are usually required to seek permission from the next signal box to admit the next train.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] When a train arrives at the end of a block section, before the signalman sends the message that the train has arrived, they must be able to see the end-of-train marker on the back of the last vehicle.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This ensures that no part of the train has become detached and remains within the section.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The end of train marker might be a coloured disc (usually red) by day or a coloured oil or electric lamp (again, usually red).
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] If a train enters the next block before the signalman sees that the disc or lamp is missing, they ask the next signal box to stop the train and investigate.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Under a permissive block system, trains are permitted to pass signals indicating the line ahead is occupied, but only at such a speed that they can stop safely should an obstacle come into view.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This allows improved efficiency in some situations and is mostly used in the United States.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] In most countries it is restricted to freight trains only, and it may be restricted depending on the level of visibility.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] In these cases, trains must proceed at very low speed (typically 32 km/h (20 mph) or less) so that they are able to stop short of any obstruction.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] In most cases, this is not allowed during times of poor visibility (e.g., fog or falling snow).
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Even with an absolute block system, multiple trains may enter a block with authorization.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This may be necessary in order to split or join trains together, or to rescue failed trains.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] In giving authorization, the signalman also ensures that the driver knows precisely what to expect ahead.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The driver must operate the train in a safe manner taking this information into account.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Generally, the signal remains at danger, and the driver is given verbal authority, usually by a yellow flag, to pass a signal at danger, and the presence of the train in front is explained.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Where trains regularly enter occupied blocks, such as stations where coupling takes place, a subsidiary signal, sometimes known as a "calling on" signal, is provided for these movements, otherwise they are accomplished through train orders.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The invention of train detection systems such as track circuits allowed the replacement of manual block systems such as absolute block with automatic block signalling.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Under automatic block signalling, signals indicate whether or not a train may enter a block based on automatic train detection indicating whether a block is clear.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The signals may also be controlled by a signalman, so that they only provide a *proceed* indication if the signalman sets the signal accordingly and the block is clear.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Most blocks are "fixed", i.e. they include the section of track between two fixed points.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] On timetable, train order, and token-based systems, blocks usually start and end at selected stations.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] On signalling-based systems, blocks start and end at signals.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The lengths of blocks are designed to allow trains to operate as frequently as necessary.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] A lightly used line might have blocks many kilometres long, but a busy commuter line might have blocks a few hundred metres long.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] A train is not permitted to enter a block until a signal indicates that the train may proceed, a dispatcher or signalman instructs the driver accordingly, or the driver takes possession of the appropriate token.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] In most cases, a train cannot enter the block until not only the block itself is clear of trains, but there is also an empty section beyond the end of the block for at least the distance required to stop the train.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] In signalling-based systems with closely spaced signals, this overlap could be as far as the signal following the one at the end of the section, effectively enforcing a space between trains of two blocks.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Historically, some lines operated so that certain large or high speed trains were signalled under different rules and only given the right of way if two blocks in front of the train were clear.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Under a moving block system, computers calculate a safe zone around each moving train that no other train is allowed to enter.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Moving block setups require instructions to be directly passed to the train instead of using lineside signals.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This has the advantage of increasing track capacity by allowing trains to run closer together while maintaining the required safety margins.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Centralized traffic control (CTC) is a form of railway signalling that originated in North America.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] CTC consolidates train routing decisions that were previously carried out by local signal operators or the train crews themselves.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The system consists of a centralized train dispatcher's office that controls railroad interlockings and traffic flows in portions of the rail system designated as CTC territory.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Train detection refers to the presence or absence of trains on a defined section of line.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The most common way to determine whether a section of line is occupied is by use of a track circuit.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The rails at either end of each section are electrically isolated from the next section, and an electric current is fed to both running rails at one end.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] A relay at the other end is connected to both rails.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] When the section is unoccupied, the relay coil completes an electrical circuit, and is energized.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] However, when a train enters the section, it short-circuits the current in the rails, and the relay is de-energized.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This method does not explicitly need to check that the entire train has left the section.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] If part of the train remains in the section, the track circuit detects that part.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This type of circuit detects the absence of trains, both for setting the signal indication and for providing various interlocking functions—for example, preventing points from being moved while a train is approaching them.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Electrical circuits also *prove* that points are locked in the appropriate position before the signal protecting that route can be cleared.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] UK trains and staff working in track circuit block areas carry track circuit operating clips (TCOC) so that, in the event of something fouling an adjacent running-line, the track circuit can be short-circuited.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This places the signal protecting that line to 'danger' to stop an approaching train before the signaller can be alerted.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] An alternate method of determining the occupied status of a block uses devices located at its beginning and end that count the number of axles that enter and leave the block section.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] If the number of axles leaving the block section equals those that entered it, the block is assumed to be clear.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Axle counters provide similar functions to track circuits, but also exhibit a few other characteristics.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] In a damp environment an axle counted section can be far longer than a track circuited one.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The low ballast resistance of very long track circuits reduces their sensitivity.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Track circuits can automatically detect some types of track defect such as a broken rail.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] In the event of power restoration after a power failure, an axle counted section is left in an undetermined state until a train has passed through the affected section.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] A track circuited section immediately detects the presence of a train in section.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] On most railways, physical signals are erected at the lineside to indicate to drivers whether the line ahead is occupied and to ensure that sufficient space exists between trains to allow them to stop.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Older forms of signal displayed their different aspects by their physical position.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The earliest types comprised a board that was either turned face-on and fully visible to the driver, or rotated so as to be practically invisible.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] While this type of signal is still in use in some countries (e.g., France and Germany), by far the most common form of mechanical signal worldwide is the semaphore signal.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This comprises a pivoted arm or blade that can be inclined at different angles.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] A horizontal arm is the most restrictive indication (for 'danger', 'caution', 'stop and proceed' or 'stop and stay' depending on the type of signal).
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] To enable trains to run at night, one or more lights are usually provided at each signal.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Typically this comprises a permanently lit oil lamp with movable coloured spectacles in front that alter the colour of the light.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The driver therefore had to learn one set of indications for daytime viewing and another for nighttime viewing.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Whilst it is normal to associate the presentation of a green light with a safe condition, this was not historically the case.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] In the very early days of railway signalling, the first coloured lights (associated with the turned signals above) presented a white light for 'clear' and a red light for 'danger'.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Green was originally used to indicate 'caution' but fell out of use when the time interval system was discontinued.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] A green light subsequently replaced white for 'clear', to address concerns that a broken red lens could be taken by a driver as a false 'clear' indication.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] It was not until scientists at Corning Glassworks perfected a shade of yellow without any tinges of green or red that yellow became the accepted colour for 'caution'.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Mechanical signals are usually remotely operated by wire from a lever in a signal box, but electrical or hydraulic operation is normally used for signals that are located too distant for manual operation.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] On most modern railways, colour light signals have largely replaced mechanical ones.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Colour light signals have the advantage of displaying the same aspects by night as by day, and require less maintenance than mechanical signals.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] On some railways, colour light signals display the same set of aspects as shown by the lights on mechanical signals during darkness.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Under **route signalling**, a driver is informed which route the train will take beyond each signal (unless only one route is possible).
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This is achieved by a *route indicator* attached to the signal.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The driver uses their route knowledge, reinforced by speed restriction signs fixed at the lineside, to drive the train at the correct speed for the route to be taken.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This method has the disadvantage that the driver may be unfamiliar with the required speed over a junction onto which they have been diverted due to some emergency condition.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Several accidents have been caused by this alone.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] For this reason, in the UK, where all lines are route signalled, drivers are only allowed to drive on routes that they have been trained on and must regularly travel over the lesser used diversionary routes to keep their route knowledge up to date.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Many route signalling systems use *approach control* (see below) to inform a driver of an upcoming change of route.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Under **speed signalling**, the signal aspect informs the driver at what speed they may proceed over a junction, but not necessarily the route the train will take.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Usually speed limit signs are used in addition to speed signals, with the driver following whichever shows the lower speed.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Many systems have come to use elements of both systems to give drivers as much information as possible.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This can mean that speed signalling systems may use route indications in conjunction with speed aspects to better inform drivers of their route; for example, route indications may be used at major stations to indicate to arriving trains to which platform they are routed.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Likewise, some route signalling systems indicate approach speed using theatre displays so that drivers know what speed they must travel.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] When the train is routed towards a diverging route that must be taken at a speed significantly less than the mainline speed, the driver must be given adequate prior warning.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Under *route signalling*, the aspects necessary to control speed do not exist, so a system known as *approach release* is often employed.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This involves holding the junction signal at a restrictive aspect (typically *stop*) so that the signals on the approach show the correct sequence of caution aspects.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The driver brakes in accordance with the caution aspect, without necessarily being aware that the diverging route has in fact been set.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] As the train approaches the junction signal, its aspect may clear to whatever aspect the current track occupancy ahead permits.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Where the turnout speed is the same, or nearly the same, as the mainline speed, approach release is unnecessary.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Under *speed signalling*, the signals approaching the divergence display aspects appropriate to control the trains speed, so no *approach release* is required.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] There is also a system of *flashing yellows* used in the UK that allows trains to approach a diverging route at higher speed.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This informs the driver that the route ahead is set onto a diverging line.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] With the advent of faster modern day trains and junctions a better system for advising drivers was required and so the following system was developed way back in the early 1980s.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The system has been refined over the years, now being used internationally and it is also used on lower speed 3-aspect signalling systems where the *single flashing yellow* is the driver's first indication.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] On the 4-aspect system, if the route through the junction is clear the junction signal will display a single *steady yellow* aspect together with an illuminated junction indicator showing the selected route.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The signal prior to the junction signal will now show a *single flashing yellow* aspect and the signal prior to that one will display *two flashing yellow* aspects.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The driver's route knowledge tells them permissible speed across the diverging junction, and they will begin to slow the train upon seeing the *two flashing yellows*.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The flashing signals tell the driver that the route through the junction is set and is clear, but that beyond that the first signal on the diverging route is *red* so they must be prepared to stop there.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] As the train approaches the junction signal, the signal may *step up* to a less restrictive aspect (single *yellow*, *two yellows* or *green*) depending on how far ahead the line is clear.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Some systems use mechanical speed control systems in conjunction with signalling to ensure the speed of a train is limited to a specific value, in order to ensure the train is travelling at a speed in which it is able to stop before an obstruction.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] These systems most often use mechanical train stop devices (a small arm coming up from the rails that will apply the brakes of a train when run over) to "trip" the brakes of a train that is travelling too fast.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Normally, once a train reaches a certain point on the tracks, it sets off a timer, when the timer runs out the train stop arm will lower, allowing a train to go past uninterrupted.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The timing is designed so that if the train is travelling at the intended speed (or slower) then the train will be able to continue without issue, but if the train is travelling too fast, then the Train Stop will trip the train and bring it to a halt.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This system can be used to ensure a train is travelling at a certain speed, which allows designers to be confident that shorter signal overlaps will be sufficient, and thus employment of this system can help to greatly improve capacity of a railway line.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The system is most often used on approach to dead end junctions to stop trains from crashing into the buffers at the end, as has happened in places such as Moorgate.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This system was modified in the early 1990s, so that an arriving train would not be able to enter the platform until the previous train had departed, however the trips continue to be used to overcome the signal overlap normally required.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] These systems are often used in conjunction with *progressive speed signalling* (see below).
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Due to the low friction between train wheels and rails, trains require large distances to stop safely.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Train drivers cannot always stop due to an obstruction they can see.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Trains run on fixed rails which guide them, so they must be routed around each other to avoid collision.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The signalling system key goal is to prevent the collision of trains, its secondary goal is to provide as much use of a given track as possible.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Service braking distance (SBD) is a critical factor in designing railway signal layouts.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Due to the low friction between rail and wheel, and the heaviness of trains, braking distance of a train can be many kilometers.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] In order to ensure safe spacing of trains, SBD must be used in calculations when placing signals.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] When signalling a line, the SBD used for that line must be the worse performing train (heaviest, weakest braking, freight trains, locomotive hauled).
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] By accounting for the worst possible train, trains with better braking (multiple units, light, advanced braking, passenger) will also be safe and protected.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Where *V* is train speed before braking and *r* is braking rate.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The minimum distance between the first signal at caution and the signal at danger is SBD.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This allows the driver to come to a halt from first seeing the caution signal to arriving at the signal at danger.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] There is also a maximum distance between signals, usually 1.5×SBD.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] While it is not intuitive to let there be a maximum distance between signals (ie, if there is a large distance between them it gives the train lots of space to stop), it is required to make sure that signals give clear information.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] If a distant signal is too far from the next stop signal, the driver may not fully brake assuming he has lots of time to brake, which could lead to an error.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] By having a maximum distance between the first caution and next signal at danger, it eliminates confusion.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] A standard braking distance for average trains (in UK signalling), travelling at a speed of 100 mph (160 km/h) can be taken as 2000 meters.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Railway blocks require a certain safety margin in case of driver error or external factors (weather conditions, leaf fall).
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Overlaps take the form of additional detection sections (track circuit or axle counters) which extend past a signal which can display a stop.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] In UK signalling the standard minimum overlap is 180 m.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Overlaps shorter than this must have additional protection measures to prevent signals passed at danger (SPAD).
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Where HD = headway distance, *V* = maximum permissible line speed.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Block distance (*D*) is the distance between two signals capable of showing red.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] It varies between two-, three- and four-aspect signalling.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] It is a critical number in designing the signalling layout.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Blocks are made up of train detection sections (often shown as a short vertical line).
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Blocks can be made of one or many detection sections.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] There are equations to determine a suitable *D* value.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Generally two-aspect signalling is used when *P* is a lot larger than SBD.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] ∗∗If *P* is 4 times or less than SBD, two-aspect signalling should not be chosen.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This is because the distance between stop signal will be so close that the distant signals starts to encroach on the previous stop signal, creating confusion for the driver.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Additionally, since every stop signal needs a distant signal, when they get so close together, it actually becomes cheaper to move on to three-aspect signalling at this point.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] When $P<4(\mathrm {SBD} )$ , it is both cheaper and safer to use three-aspect signalling.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This is not a hard rule, it is still technically possible to use two aspects at this point, but not recommended.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Three-aspect signalling creates significantly increased capacity over two-aspect signalling.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Four-aspect signalling adds an additional warning signal, which is often a double yellow.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This further divides up the railway and allows for more capacity.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] For example, we have a railway with maximum speed (*V*) of 160 km/h (44 m/s).
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Given a train with standard braking, the service braking distance (SBD) is 2000 m.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Standard sighting distance (*S*) of 300 m.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] If a train is required to run every 1 hour (3600 s), what distance must signals be placed to achieve this headway?
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Generally the option with the least cost is chosen first.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Since *P* is large ( $>4\mathrm {SBD}$ ), we should choose two-aspect.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] For example, we have a railway with maximum speed (*V*) of 200 km/h (56 m/s).
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Standard sighting distance (*S*) of 400 m.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] If we ask asked to run a train every 2 minutes (or 30 trains an hour), what distance must signals be placed to achieve this headway?
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] We have found *P*, now we must choose the cheapest aspect type for which *P* and SBD satisfy all equations.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Since *P* (5787 m) is less than 4SBD (4 × 3085 m = 12340 m), we cannot use two-aspect since the distant signals will be too close to the previous stop signals, creating confusion for the driver.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The flexibility on range allows signals to be moved around if other external factors require the signal to be moved.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Once headway calculations are done, other infrastructure must be accounted for (why a flexible range of block distance is required).
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Railway junctions are moveable infrastructure which must be protected by signals.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] If a train goes over a railway switch/point and that point is in the wrong position, it can damage the points or cause derailment.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Junctions must be protected by a signal capable of displaying a *stop* aspect.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The signal will let the driver know if it is safe to traverse the junction.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Using train detection areas, the signalling interlocking can determine if it is safe for a train to pass.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] For converging junctions, the minimum distance for a protecting signal away from the junction is the overlap distance (in UK signalling it is usually 180m).
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] It is measured from the clearance point (CP) of the junction.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] There is not necessarily a maximum specified distance to a converging junction.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The train does not need to slow down regardless of the position of the points.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Even if a train passes over the switches in the wrong position, the force of the train will force the switches over.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The fouling point (FP) is the position where two trains would have a side-on collision when approaching a junction.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] It is measured perpendicularly away from the rails.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The clearance point (CP) is the position in which a train can stop safely in front of a junction to allow another train to safely pass by.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The CP is measured a set distance away from the FP.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Signals protecting the junction must be placed at least the length of the overlap away from the clearance point.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] For diverging junctions, the minimum distance for a protecting signal away from the junction is the overlap distance (in UK signalling it is usually 180m).
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The diagrams use show route signalling as examples.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] For diverging junctions, the maximum distance for a protecting signal away from the junction is a specified distance, which is set by the local railway standards (in UK signalling it is 800m).
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Drivers must slow down when taking the diverging route on a set of points (when not going straight through).
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Therefore a maximum specified distance is required to make sure the instructions to the driver are clear and not forgotten.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] So when placing signals that protect diverging junctions, the distance must be between *180m and 800m* (UK signalling).
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The position of signals is initially found by using headway calculations, then taking into account the track layout (points, gradients, speed limits), operational requirements, rolling stock and capacity requirements.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] A train driver failing to respond to a signal's indication can be catastrophic.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] As a result, various auxiliary safety systems have been devised.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Any such system requires installation of some degree of train borne and wayside equipment.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Some systems only intervene in the event of a signal being passed at danger (SPAD).
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Others include audible and/or visual indications inside the driver's cab to supplement the line side signals.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Automatic brake application occurs if the driver should fail to acknowledge a warning.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The most advanced train control systems have no driver at all relying on computers to drive the system entirely such as Skytrain in Vancouver, Canada and the metro system in Doha, Qatar.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] In-cab safety systems are of great benefit during fog, when poor visibility would otherwise require that restrictive measures be put in place.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Safety systems are also important in urban rail where it is impossible to see around corners in subway and metro tunnels.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] On-board and wayside computers can track trains around tight corners at higher speeds ensuring safety.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Cab signalling is a subsystem that communicates signalling information into the train cab such as driving position, speed and failure alarms.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Cab signaling units are important human factors engineering subsystems in modern train signalling systems.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] If there is an active cab, the orientation of the train is decided, i.e. the side of the active cab is considered as the front of the train.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] In modern systems, a train protection system is overlaid on top of the cab signalling system and will automatically apply the brakes and bring the train to a stop if the driver fails to control the speed of the train in accordance with the system's safety requirements.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Cab signalling systems rely on tachometers, accelerometers, ultra-wideband units, inertia measurement units, track circuits, to transponders that communicate with the cab, and communication-based train control systems.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] In the early days of the railways, signalmen were responsible for ensuring any points (US: switches) were set correctly before allowing a train to proceed.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Mistakes, however, led to accidents, sometimes with fatalities.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] The concept of the mechanical interlocking of point switches, signals and other appliances was introduced to improve safety.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] This prevents a signalman from operating appliances in an unsafe sequence using mechanical means, such as clearing a signal while one or more sets of points are not set correctly for the route.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Early interlocking systems used mechanical devices both to operate the signalling appliances and to ensure their safe operation.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Beginning around the 1930s, electrical relay interlockings were used.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Since the mid 1980s, new interlocking systems have tended to be of the electronic variety.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Microprocessors decide what point switch movements are permissible.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p01] Modern interlocking systems and subsystems allow and prohibit certain point switch positions to enhance train safety.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p02] Operating rules, policies and procedures are used by railroads to enhance safety.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p02] Specific operating rules often differ from country to country, and there may even be differences between separate railroads within the same country.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p02] The application of operating rules in Australia is called *Safeworking*.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p02] The *method of working* for any particular region or location is referred-to as the "Safeworking system" for that region.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p02] Operating rules differ between states, although attempts are being made to formulate a national standard.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p02] In North America, and especially the United States, operating rules are called *method of operation*.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p02] The operating rulebook for the United Kingdom is called the "GE/RT8000 Rule Book", more commonly known simply as "The Rule Book" by railway employees.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p02] It is controlled by the Rail Safety and Standards Board (RSSB), which is independent from Network Rail or any other train operating company or freight operating company.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p02] Most heritage railways operate to a simplified variant of a British Railways rule book.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p02] The signalling system used on the railway network in Finland comprises color-light signals and fixed signs.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p02] It is used together with the EBICAB 900, an automatic train control system better known as JKV, Finnish: *junakulunvalvonta*.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p02] In Italy, railway signalling is described in a particular instruction called *Regolamento Segnali* Archived December 7, 2014, at the Wayback Machine (*Signal Regulation*).
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p02] The Indian operating rules, called the "General Rules", are common for all zonal railways of Indian Railways and can be amended only by the Railway Board.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p02] Subsidiary rules are added to the General Rules by zonal railways, which do not infringe upon them.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p02] Corrections are brought about from time to time through correction slips.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p02] Japanese signalling was initially based on British railway signalling practice, and Japanese railway signalling continues to be based on the UK route signalling system for junctions.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p02] However, as signalling has advanced to meet the requirements of the system, progressive speed signalling is used outside of junctions.
[src:en-50128-railway/railway-signalling-p02] Hong Kong Railway signalling originated from the British railway signalling principle, and continues to be based on the principles to develop rulebooks and procedures under the operating organisation MTR.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] In functional safety, **safety integrity level** (**SIL**) is defined as the relative level of risk-reduction provided by a safety instrumented function (SIF), i.e. the measurement of the performance required of the SIF.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] In the functional safety standards based on the IEC 61508 standard, four SILs are defined, with SIL4 being the most dependable and SIL1 the least.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] The applicable SIL is determined based on a number of quantitative factors in combination with qualitative factors, such as risk assessments and safety lifecycle management.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] Other standards, however, may have different SIL number definitions.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] Assignment, or allocation of SIL is an exercise in risk analysis where the risk associated with a specific hazard, which is intended to be protected against by a SIF, is calculated without the beneficial risk reduction effect of the SIF.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] That unmitigated risk is then compared against a tolerable risk target.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] The difference between the unmitigated risk and the tolerable risk, if the unmitigated risk is higher than tolerable, must be addressed through risk reduction of provided by the SIF.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] This amount of required risk reduction is correlated with the SIL target.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] In essence, each order of magnitude of risk reduction that is required correlates with an increase in SIL, up to a maximum of SIL4.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] Should the risk assessment establish that the required SIL cannot be achieved by a SIL4 SIF, then alternative arrangements must be designed, such as non-instrumented safeguards (e.g, a pressure relief valve).
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] There are several methods used to assign a SIL.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] Of the methods presented above, LOPA is by far the most commonly used in large industrial facilities, such as for example chemical process plants.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] The assignment may be tested using both pragmatic and controllability approaches, applying industry guidance such as the one published by the UK HSE.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] SIL assignment processes that use the HSE guidance to ratify assignments developed from risk matrices have been certified to meet IEC 61508.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] There are several problems inherent in the use of safety integrity levels.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] According to IEC 61508, the SIL concept must be related to the dangerous failure rate of a system, not just its failure rate or the failure rate of a component part, such as the software.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] Definition of the dangerous failure modes by safety analysis is intrinsic to the proper determination of the failure rate.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] The International Electrotechnical Commission's (IEC) standard IEC 61508 defines SIL using requirements grouped into two broad categories: *hardware safety integrity* and *systematic safety integrity*.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] A device or system must meet the requirements for *both* categories to achieve a given SIL.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] The SIL requirements for hardware safety integrity are based on a probabilistic analysis of the device.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] In order to achieve a given SIL, the device must meet targets for the maximum probability of dangerous failure and a minimum safe failure fraction.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] The concept of 'dangerous failure' must be rigorously defined for the system in question, normally in the form of requirement constraints whose integrity is verified throughout system development.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] The actual targets required vary depending on the likelihood of a demand, the complexity of the device(s), and types of redundancy used.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] Hazards of a control system must be identified then analysed through risk analysis.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] Mitigation of these risks continues until their overall contribution to the hazard are considered acceptable.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] The tolerable level of these risks is specified as a safety requirement in the form of a target 'probability of a dangerous failure' in a given period of time, stated as a discrete SIL.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] Certification schemes, such as the CASS Scheme (Conformity Assessment of Safety-related Systems) are used to establish whether a device meets a particular SIL.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] Third parties that can provide certification include Bureau Veritas, CSA Group, TÜV Rheinland, TÜV SÜD and UL among others.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] The requirements of these schemes can be met either by establishing a rigorous development process, or by establishing that the device has sufficient operating history to argue that it has been proven in use.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] Electric and electronic devices can be certified for use in functional safety applications according to IEC 61508.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] There are a number of application-specific standards based on or adapted from IEC 61508, such as IEC 61511 for the process industry sector.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] This standard is used in the petrochemical and hazardous chemical industries, among others.
[src:en-50128-railway/safety-integrity-level] The following standards use SIL as a measure of reliability and/or risk reduction.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] System Safety is the overarching discipline that aims to achieve safety by reducing risks in technical systems to an acceptable level.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] According to the widely adopted system safety standard IEC 61508, safety is “freedom from unacceptable risk of harm”.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] As software alone – which can be considered as pure information – cannot cause any harm by itself, the term software safety is sometimes dismissed and replaced by “software system safety” (e.g. the Joint Software Systems Safety Engineering Handbook and MIL-STD-882E use this terminology).
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] This stresses that software can only cause harm in the context of a technical system (see NASA Software Safety Guidebook, chapter 2.1.2), that has some effect on its environment.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] The goal of software safety is to make sure that software does not cause or contribute to any hazards in the system where it is used and that it can be assured and demonstrated that this is the case.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] This is typically achieved by the assignment of a "safety level" to the software and the selection of appropriate processes for the development and assurance of the software.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] One of the first steps when creating safety-related software is to classify software according to its safety-criticality.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] Various standards suggest different levels, e.g.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] Software Levels A-E in DO-178C, SIL (Safety Integrity Level) 1-4 in IEC 61508, ASIL (Automotive Safety Integrity Level) A-D in ISO 26262.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] The assignment is typically done in the context of an overarching system, where the worst case consequences of software failures are investigated.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] For example, automotive standard ISO 26262 requires the performance of a Hazard and Risk Assessment ("HARA") on vehicle level to derive the ASIL of the software executed on a component.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] It is essential to use an adequate development and assurance process, with appropriate methods and techniques, commensurate with the safety criticality of the software.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] Software safety standards recommend and sometimes forbid the use of such methods and techniques, depending on the safety level.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] Most standards suggest a lifecycle model (e.g.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] EN 50716, SIL (Safety Integrity Level) 1-4 in IEC 61508 suggests – among others – a V-model) and prescribe required activities to be executed during the various phases of the software.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] The focus on the software development and assurance process stems from the fact that software quality (and hence safety) is heavily influenced by the software process, as suggested by IEC 25010.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] It is claimed that the process influences the internal software quality attributes (e.g. code quality) and these in turn influence external software quality attributes (e.g. functionality and reliability).
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] The following activities and topics addressed in the development process contribute to safe software.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] Comprehensive documentation of the complete development and assurance process is required by virtually all software safety standards.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] Typically, this documentation is reviewed and endorsed by third parties and therefore a prerequisite for the approval of safety-related software.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] The documentation ranges from various planning documents, requirements specifications, software architecture and design documentation, test cases on various abstraction levels, tool qualification reports, review evidence, verification and validation results etc.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] Fig C.2 in EN 50716 lists 32 documents that need to be created along the development lifecycle.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] Traceability is the practice to establish relationships between different types of requirements and between requirements and design, implementation and testing artefacts.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] According to EN 50716, the objective “is to ensure that all requirements can be shown to have been properly met and that no untraceable material has been introduced”.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] Safety standards can have requirements directly affecting the implementation of the software in source code, such as e.g. the selection of an appropriate programming language, the size and complexity of functions, the use of certain programming constructs and the need for coding standards.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] Appropriate test coverage needs to be demonstrated, i.e. depending on the safety level more rigorous testing schemes have to be applied.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] Software safety standards typically require some activities to be executed with independence, i.e. by a different person, by a person with different reporting lines, or even by an independent organization.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] This ensures that conflicts of interest are avoided and increases the chances that faults (e.g. in the software design) are identified.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] For example, EN 50716 Figure 2 requires the roles “implementer”, “tester” and “verifier” to be held by different people, the role “validator” to be held by a person with different reporting line and the role “assessor” to be held by a person from a different organizational unit.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] DO-178C and DO-278A require several activities (e.g. test coverage verification, assurance activities) to be executed “with independence”, with independence being defined as “separation of responsibilities which ensures the accomplishment of objective evaluation”.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] In system safety engineering, it is common to allocate upper bounds for failure rates of subsystems or components.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] It must then be shown that these subsystems or components do not exceed their allocated failure rates, or otherwise redundancy or other fault tolerance mechanisms must be employed.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] This approach is not practicable for software.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] Software failure rates cannot be predicted with any confidence.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] Although significant research in the field of software reliability has been conducted (see for example Lyu (1996), current software safety standards do not require any of these methods to be used or even discourage their usage, e.g.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] 73) states: “Many methods for predicting software reliability based on developmental metrics have been published, for example, software structure, defect detection rate, etc.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] This document does not provide guidance for those types of methods, because at the time of writing, currently available methods did not provide results in which confidence can be placed.” ARP 4761 clause 4.1.2 states that software design errors “are not the same as hardware failures.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] Software safety and security may have differing interests in some cases.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] On the one hand safety-related software that is not secure can pose a safety risk, on the other hand, some security practices (e.g. frequent and timely patching) contradict established safety practices (rigorous testing and verification before anything is changed in an operational system).
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] Software that employs artificial intelligence techniques such as machine learning follows a radically different lifecycle.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] In addition, the behavior is harder to predict than for a traditionally developed system.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] Hence, the question whether and how these technologies can be used, is under current investigation.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] Currently, standards generally do not endorse their use.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] For example, EN 50716 (Table A.3) states that artificial intelligence and machine learning are not recommended for any safety integrity level.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] Agile software development, which typically features many iterations, is sometimes still stigmatized as being too chaotic for safety-related software development.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] This might be partially caused by statements such as "working software over comprehensive documentation", which is found in the manifesto for agile development.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] Although most software safety standards present the software lifecycle in the traditional waterfall-like sequence, some do contain statements that allow for more flexible lifecycles.
[src:en-50128-railway/software-safety] DO-178C states that "The processes of a software life cycle may be iterative, that is, entered and reentered." EN 50716 contains Annex C that shows how iterative development lifecycles can be used in line with the requirements of the standard.
